+      "title": "Inheritance Changes the Tier on Every File You Bundled",
+      "content": "Week 5 of the AI governance pilot is iterate and scope. The Week 4 build goes to a teammate, breaks somewhere, and gets fixed. The pilot hub flags a governance question most builders miss in that handoff: iteration changes who can use what. If your v2 expands the audience, the data tier of every reference file inside the build expands with it.\n\nThe framework is unambiguous on what each tier permits. Tier 4 public materials carry no restriction. Tier 3 internal documents like strategic plans, program models, and de-identified aggregate outcomes sit under open access for DC CAP licensed users. Tier 2 sensitive content covers budget models, MOU terms, and small-cell aggregates with N below 10, all requiring role-specific access and de-identification verification before upload. Tier 1 PII and FERPA-protected records stay prohibited from Claude in any form.\n\nA Project that worked for one author with a tight reference pack assumes the author's trust permissions. The moment a teammate inherits it, those permissions stop being implicit. A budget model loaded for a Director's planning use becomes a Tier 2 file in a coaching team's hands. A partner MOU referenced for a single email becomes a re-disclosure when the Project ships to four colleagues.\n\nThe discipline is mechanical. Before broadening access, list every file in the Project's reference panel, tag each one to a tier, and decide whether the new audience is authorized for the highest tier on the list. If anything is Tier 2, role-restrict access. If anything is Tier 1, remove it and rebuild the reference around aggregated or public substitutes.",
+      "tryThis": "Open the Project you'll hand to a teammate this week. List every file in the reference panel. Tag each one Tier 1, 2, 3, or 4 against Section 6 of the framework. If the highest-tier file in the pack outranks the audience you're expanding to, role-restrict access or rebuild the reference around aggregated or public substitutes before you ship the v2.",
+      "date": "2026-05-06",
+      "resource": "https://dccapinnovation.org/ai_governance_framework.html#data-classification",
+      "sourceNotes": "Claim: Week 5 of the AI governance pilot is iterate and scope; the Week 4 build goes to a teammate and gets fixed | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 5 section: \"Week 4 was build. Week 5 is iterate. Take what you built, give it to a teammate, watch where it breaks, fix it.\")\nClaim: \"Iteration changes who can use what. If your v2 expands the audience, the data tier of every reference file expands with it.\" | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 5 \"Governance Pulse\" callout, verbatim)\nClaim: Tier 4 is unrestricted; covers public materials | Source: GROUNDED (ai_governance_framework.html Section 6 data-classification table, Tier 4 row: \"UNRESTRICTED — All users. Standard retention.\")\nClaim: Tier 3 internal includes strategic plans, program models, de-identified aggregate outcomes; open access for DC CAP licensed users | Source: GROUNDED (ai_governance_framework.html Section 6, Tier 3 row examples and \"OPEN ACCESS — All licensed users within DC CAP\")\nClaim: Tier 2 covers budget models, MOU terms, small-cell aggregates N<10; requires role-specific access and de-identification verification before upload | Source: GROUNDED (ai_governance_framework.html Section 6, Tier 2 row examples and access rule: \"RESTRICTED ACCESS — Role-specific access with least access default ... Requires de-identification verification before upload.\")\nClaim: Tier 1 PII and FERPA-protected records are prohibited from Claude in any form | Source: GROUNDED (ai_governance_framework.html Section 6, Tier 1 row: \"PROHIBITED — Never upload to Claude in any form. No exceptions without legal review and explicit board authorization.\")\nClaim: A Project's reference files carry the data tier of whatever you load | Source: GROUNDED (pilot_hub.html Week 3 framework card description: \"Containers bake governance in. A Project's reference files carry the data tier of whatever you load.\")\nClaim: Inheritance scenario examples (budget model in coaching team's hands, MOU re-disclosure when Project ships to colleagues) | Source: Editorial (illustrative scenarios applying Section 6 tier rules to Week 5 inheritance dynamics named in the Governance Pulse)",
