       "category": "tips",
       "content": "Week 4 asks every participant to build something worth keeping. The challenge requires loading at least one outside source (a research doc, a peer playbook, a verified data table, the brand guide, an Anthropic skill) and writing it into the procedure. The trap is pasting the source into a reference file and assuming Claude will read it. Outputs sound the same as before. The build does not earn its keep.\n\nExtraction is the move. A source changes output when you pull the specific rules, numbers, and anti-patterns out of it and write them into the custom-instructions block or SKILL.md procedure. Three lines of doing.\n\nStep one: open Claude with the source loaded. Ask: \"Read this document. Extract every concrete instruction, threshold, or anti-pattern that should change how a draft on [your task] gets written. List them as bullets, with the page or section number for each.\" This produces a list you can audit. Numbers, named patterns, prohibitions: the parts of the source that have an opinion.\n\nStep two: filter. Strike anything generic. Keep what is specific to your task and verifiable against the source.\n\nStep three: write the kept items into the procedure. In a Project, add them under the custom-instructions block as standards the draft must meet. In a Skill, write them into the SKILL.md as named rules. Cite the source so the next reader can trace any rule back to where it came from.\n\nThe build now carries the source's authority. A teammate inheriting it gets the rules and the citation in one move. That is what Week 4 means by a build that earns its keep.",
